When anonymous access is enabled it can cause a breaking change in authentication workflow:

*Anonymous disabled:*
 * non-authenticated user attempts using api on resource


 ** ex [http://mill.jfrog.info:12116/artifactory/api/storage/example-repo-local]
 * Artifactory returns a challenge for credentials

*Anonymous Enabled*
 * non-authenticated user ** attempts to use same API
 * Artifactory sees this as "anonymous" user
 * Artifactory returns error with no challenge:

{code:java}
{
  "errors" : [ {
    "status" : 403,
    "message" : "Request for 'example-repo-local:' is forbidden for user 'anonymous'."
  } ]
}
{code}
This means that enabling anonymous can drastically affect workflows and automation.

The request is that if anonymous attempts access on a restricted resource, the request would fall back to a non-authenticated user, thus issuing a credential challenge.

I currently have a few issues with the "users" DSL resource, 

First, if your organization uses an external for user management, such as Crowd, the ability to set specified users as admins requires the user to login in order for their user object to be imported.  Only after this can the user be configured as an admin.  It would be great if another parameter such as "realm" could be specified so that you could easily automate this process from MC.

Secondly, when running the "user" DSL resource, it would be great to have the ability to only update the attributes which have been specified.  For example, providing this block:
{code:java}
users {
  user('johndoe') {
    admin true
  }
}{code}
will result in Mission Control still prompting you for the user email and password prior to executing the script.  This isn't optimal as in cases like this one, all that should be done is update the user to have admin rights.

Currently, with the permission Mission Control DSL block must be supplied with a list of repository names via the "repositories" option.   In cases where you have many defined repositories and have more custom rules as to when they are to be included, it's very useful to have the ability to regular expressions to match against the repo names. 

For example, say you have over a hundred repositories defined, and you have a specific permission named "security", for which you wanted it to include only the following list of repos:
 * yum-security-updates-local
 * yum-security-packages-local
 * yum-security-remote
 * docker-security-local

Currently, the resource would then have to be specified like this:
{code:java}
  permissions {
    permission('security') {
      includesPattern '**'
      excludesPattern ''
      anyLocal false
      anyRemote false
      anyDistribution false
      repositories (["yum-security-updates-local", "yum-security-packages-local", "yum-security-remote", "docker-security-local"])
      groups {
        admins (['manage', 'delete', 'deploy', 'annotate', 'read']) 
      }
    }
  }
{code}
Although having the ability to specify repository name inclusions/exclusions regexes could help simplify this.  For example, something like this would be useful:
{code:java}
  permissions {
    permission('security') {
      includesPattern '**'
      excludesPattern ''
      anyLocal false
      anyRemote false
      anyDistribution false
      repositoriesIncludesPatterns ([".*-security-.*"])
      groups {
        admins (['manage', 'delete', 'deploy', 'annotate', 'read']) 
      }
    }
  }{code}
Or also to specify exclusions, calculated after the inclusions, something like this:
{code:java}
  permissions {
    permission('security') {
      includesPattern '**'
      excludesPattern ''
      anyLocal false
      anyRemote false
      anyDistribution false
      repositoriesIncludesPatterns ([".*-security-.*"])
      repositoriesIncludesPatterns ([".*-remote$"])
      groups {
        admins (['manage', 'delete', 'deploy', 'annotate', 'read']) 
      }
    }
  }{code}
This second example would then narrow down the inclusion to only the following repository names:
 * yum-security-updates-local
 * yum-security-packages-local
 * docker-security-local

Currently, implemented code in my MissionControl script to simulate this logic, although it would be much more convenient to have it built in to the resource.  Another option could be to modify the current *includesPattern*/*excludesPattern* to accept list of regular expressions which could also match on the repository name.

As a note, this ticket is similar to RTFACT-12515, which i also related to regular expressions although only for the existing *includesPattern*/*excludesPattern* that only affects the artifact path.

Background:

I am using Artifactory in docker, along with the provided nginx reverse proxy. The automatic configuration of nginx by Artifactory is very convenient. However, it does not always work the way I want it to. In HA mode, for example, I do not want nginx to act as a load balancer, since I already use a load balancer in front of nginx. My solution was to override the /updateConf.sh script in the nginx docker image, to modify the config output returned by Artifactory before it is written to disk. Using sed :(.

 

Feature request:

Allow the user to specify an nginx (or other reverse proxy) config template (such as Mustache, Jinja, or similar), which will expand based on context variables passed in by Artifactory.

 

Examples:

The default template might look something like this:

 
{code:java}
{% if ha.enabled %}
## add HA entries when ha is configure
upstream artifactory {
   {% for server in ha.servers %}
   server {{ server.hostname}}:{{ server.port }};
   {% endfor %}
}
{% endif %}

{% for server in virtual_servers %}
## server configuration
server {

    listen {{ server.port }};
    
    server_name {{ server_name }};

    # ... More stuff here ...
}
{% endfor %}{code}
 

Now if the user wished to change the nginx configuration, they could modify and upload a new template, provided they use the variables that are provided by Artifactory.

 

In my case, I would have modified the above to look more like:
{code:java}
{% if ha.enabled %}
## add HA entries when ha is configure
upstream artifactory {
   server artifactory:{{ server.port }};
}
{% endif %}

{% for server in virtual_servers %}
## server configuration
server {

