Docker images have digests based on the sha256 of the manifest. When pulling images from a registry, you can "pull by digest", or use the digest instead of a tag. For example, the current version of the {{alpine:latest}} image on Docker Hub has digest:
{noformat}
sha256:3dcdb92d7432d56604d4545cbd324b14e647b313626d99b889d0626de158f73a
{noformat}
I can use this in a {{docker pull}} command, like so:
{noformat}
docker pull alpine@sha256:3dcdb92d7432d56604d4545cbd324b14e647b313626d99b889d0626de158f73a
{noformat}
Doing this ensures that I get the exact same version of the image. This is true because, if a new version of the image-tag pair is pushed to the Docker Hub, the old version hangs around and remains accessible via pull-by-digest.

This all works on Artifactory. However, when I push a new version of an image into Artifactory, the old manifest file and any layers that aren't used by the new image are placed into the trash. Pulling by digest for the old version of the image works, but only until the trash is cleared.

It would be nice if a new push for an existing image-tag pair tapped into Artifactory's support for versioning and made the pushed image act as a new version of the Docker image. Then we could prune old images properly and, ideally, select in the repository settings how many versions of a given tag we want to keep.

